My comment #9 is only a workaround, so I did some more research.

Restart pcscd without using pcscd_flags="--disable-polkit".
# By the way, it is still holding on to the terminal, so I'm restarting it like daemon service pcscd restart.

Create a file with the contents as described in ${WRKSRC}/doc/README.polkit .

I made /usr/local/etc/polkit-1/rules.d/60-pcsc-lite.rules with the following contents.

polkit.addRule(
        function (action, subject) {
                if (action.id == "org.debian.pcsc-lite.access_card" &&
                        subject.user == "tatsuki") {
                        return polkit.Result.YES;
                }
        });
polkit.addRule(
        function (action, subject) {
                if (action.id == "org.debian.pcsc-lite.access_pcsc" &&
                        subject.user == "tatsuki") {
                        return polkit.Result.YES;
                }
        });

polkitd doesn't have the ability to automatically re-read the file it created, or it doesn't have the ability to force the file to be re-read, so it needs to be terminated once.
SIGINT is a signal to terminate normally.

killall -INT polkitd

These allowed a user named tatsuki to reach the PC/SC interface.
It seems that it was important to terminate polkitd once the rule file was rewritten.
polkitd will be re-booted by dbus.
